   Zwiren Joins Needham
                                                                                                       

   Jan Zwiren has resigned as chief executive officer of
Ayer's Chicago office to join Omnicom's DDB Needham unit,
adding to speculation that Ayer may sell its Chicago
operation.
   But Ayer spokesperson Victoria Horstmann denied rumors
that Ayer would shed its Chicago office. "We're staying in
Chicago," she said. "We're trying to shore it up with added
sevices, like creative media research out of New York. We're
reinforcing the ties between New York and Chicago."
   Ms. Zwiren, who wasn't available for comment, left Zwiren
Ayer, as the Chicago office had been known, to become
director of strategic business development at DDB Needham's
Chicago office. New York-based Ayer's Chicago office will now
be known as Ayer Chicago, and its chief operating officer,
Frank Maher, assumes the top post of general manager.
   Ayer acquired Ms. Zwiren's small agency less than two
years ago, merging it with its own Chicago office and having
Ms. Zwiren report directly to the president of Ayer U.S.A.,
Dom Rossi. Her successor, Mr. Maher, will report to Dean
Proctor, an executive vice president in Ayer's New York
office. Ayer Chairman Jerry Siano couldn't be reached for
comment on rumors that the Chicago operation may be sold.
   In addition, Tim Prosch, director of account services in
the Chicago office, and John Trusk, creative director, were
named managing directors.
   ---
   Possible Ad Ban in Oregon
                                                                                                       

   Voters in Oregon may get the chance to vote on whether to
ban virtually all alcohol and tobacco advertising in their
state. But the Association of National Advertisers is
fighting to keep the issue off the ballot.
   Two Oregon residents, Anthony Taylor and Cheryl MacDonald,
are collecting signatures to get their proposed ban on the
ballot for the November 1992 election. Included would be all
forms of media advertising for alcohol and tobacco products,
except "ads on packages that aren't used for display," and
logos on letterhead and in trade journals.
   But the advertiser group's executive vice president,
Daniel L. Jaffe, has urged Oregon's secretary of state to
refuse to accept the ballot initiative, claiming it violates
the state's constitution and that it "raises serious concerns
about the constitutional protections afforded by the U.S.
Supreme Court to commercial speech."
   A draft of the proposed initiative contends: "Promoting or
glamourizing cigarettes, tobacco products and alcohol adds to
social problems and conflicts with sensible drug policy.
Effects of these acts should be minimized." The ANA hopes to
pursue the matter with Oregon officials.
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   TOY REVIEW: Takara U.S.A. Corp., the U.S. unit of
Tokyo-based toy maker Takara Co., is reviewing 10 agencies to
handle its line of gift items and toys. Takara is in its
first year in the U.S., although its battery-operated
"dancing" beverage cans and flowers have been available
through U.S. distributors.
